# NoteFlow — Cursor AI Rules

You are building **NoteFlow**, a minimalist daily productivity web app. Read `docs/idea.md` for product scope.

## Product constraints (never violate)

- **One stream:** All content lives in "The Universal Flow" — chronological, no folder hierarchy.
- **Three entry types only:** `note`, `task`, `link`. Do not add calendars, tags-as-folders, rich docs, or other types in v1.
- **Capture first:** UI must minimize friction (+ NOTE, + TASK, + LINK).
- **Filters are views, not storage:** ALL / NOTES / TASKS / LINKS filter the same data; never split into separate stores per type.
- **v1 is local-only:** Persist with `localStorage`. No auth, backend, or cloud sync unless explicitly requested.

## Tech stack

| Layer | Choice |
|-------|--------|
| Framework | React 18+ (functional components, hooks) |
| Language | TypeScript (`strict: true`) |
| Build | Vite |
| Styling | Plain CSS / CSS modules (no Tailwind unless already in repo) |
| State | React context + hooks, or Zustand if global state grows |
| Persistence | `localStorage` adapter in `src/lib/storage/` |
| Tests | Vitest + React Testing Library (when tests are requested) |

> NoteFlow v1 targets **web** (sidebar + main layout, `localStorage`, external links). Do not use React Native primitives (`View`, `Text`, `StyleSheet`) unless the stack changes.

## Planned folder structure

```
src/
  components/     # Shared UI (Sidebar, EntryCard, FlowFeed…)
  features/       # Feature slices (capture, filters, stats)
  hooks/          # Reusable hooks (useEntries, useFilter…)
  lib/            # Pure utils (groupByDate, validateUrl, storage)
  store/          # Global state (if not colocated in features)
  types/          # Entry, NoteEntry, TaskEntry, LinkEntry
  styles/         # Global tokens, reset
```

- **Feature-first** for new code; avoid a flat `components/` dump of unrelated files.
- **Colocate** tests as `*.test.ts(x)` next to the file under test.

## Domain model

```typescript
type EntryType = 'note' | 'task' | 'link';

interface BaseEntry {
  id: string;
  type: EntryType;
  createdAt: string; // ISO 8601
}

// note → { body: string }
// task → { title: string; items: { id: string; text: string; done: boolean }[] }
// link → { title: string; url: string }
```

- IDs: `crypto.randomUUID()` or equivalent.
- Sort entries **newest first** within each date group.
- Stats: `entries.length`, tasks done = items where `done === true`.

## TypeScript rules

- No `any`. Use `unknown` at boundaries and narrow with type guards or Zod if parsing external JSON.
- Explicit prop interfaces for every component.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes; use discriminated unions on `type` for entry variants.
- Enable `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` when configuring `tsconfig`.

## React patterns

- Functional components only; extract logic into custom hooks when a component exceeds ~80 lines.
- Prefer composition over prop drilling; context for entries + filter state.
- Memoize list items (`React.memo`) only when profiling shows need — feed is the hot path.
- No class components, no default exports for components (use named exports).

## UI / design system

Match the wireframe: **monochrome brutalist** aesthetic.

- Colors: white `#FFFFFF`, black `#000000`, accent red/orange for active filter + progress bar.
- Borders: `1px solid #000`, **no border-radius** on buttons/cards.
- Typography: uppercase labels (NOTEFLOW, THE UNIVERSAL FLOW, STATS, ADD); monospace or clean sans.
- Layout: fixed left sidebar + scrollable main feed.
- Entry cards: black header bar with type label (NOTE / TASK / LINK) + time on the right.
- Do not introduce gradients, shadows, rounded cards, or heavy animation libraries.

## Code style

- **Minimize diff scope** — only change what the task requires.
- Match existing naming: `camelCase` functions/vars, `PascalCase` components, `kebab-case` file names for non-components.
- Self-explanatory code; comments only for non-obvious business rules.
- No premature abstractions (no wrapper hooks for one-liners).

## What to avoid

- Redux, MobX, or heavy state libraries for v1.
- Next.js / SSR — this is a client-side Vite SPA.
- Adding npm dependencies without clear need.
- Creating markdown/docs files unless asked.
- Contradicting decisions in `docs/idea.md` or `docs/project-management.md`.

## References

- Product: `docs/idea.md`
- Kanban / features: `docs/project-management.md`
- AI setup: `docs/ai-setup.md`

When unsure about scope, prefer the simplest implementation that satisfies v1 in `docs/idea.md`.
